{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Ks7LE13PQ9nZgbBzyPUbP8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me implement the 4 changes:\n\n1. **Fix A** (passesHardFilters, ~line 180): Add breadcrumb filter for 2+ slashes\n2. **Fix B** (isLikelyGarbled, after line 139): Add mid-word casing transition check\n3. **Fix C** (buildCandidates, before the for loop at line 294): Add metadata continuation suppression\n4. **Fix D** (METADATA_PATTERNS, after line 59): Add OCR-resilient DLA patterns\n\nLet me also check if there's a potential issue with Fix A and the SAFFRON test case. \n\nLooking at the test case, the line with a single slash won't trigger the 2+ slash filter, and the continuation merge that happens earlier will combine it into a single line with just one slash, so it passes through fine. wait - `TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART` has one slash, so it won't be filtered. Good.\n\nBut there's also the `capsCoalesced` step. Let me trace through the SAFFRON test:\n1. `TITLE FIRST PART` - isAllCaps=true, wordCount=3 > 2, so it does NOT go into the capsCoalesced merge logic\n2. `/ SECOND PART` - starts with `/`, not ALL_CAPS\n3. Then in mergedLines, `TITLE FIRST PART` is followed by `/ SECOND PART` which starts with `/`, so they get merged into `TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART`\n\nWhen `passesHardFilters` is called on `TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART`, this has 1 slash → not filtered. Good.\n\nNow let me check what happens with `/ Jesien / Zupy`. It has mixed case letters, so `isAllCaps` is false, and it would normally get merged with whatever precedes it. In the failure case where this appears at the start of the document, it's followed by `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA`, so I need to trace how these lines interact through the filtering and merging logic. - Position 1: `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA`\n\nIn the mergedLines pre-merge step (lines 278-289), it checks if the NEXT line starts with `/&+:(`. So for position 0 `/ Jesien / Zupy`, we check if position 1 starts with `/&+:(`. `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA` doesn't start with those chars, so no merge happens.\n\nBut then `/ Jesien / Zupy` is a candidate. In `passesHardFilters`:\n- length: \"/ Jesien / Zupy\" = 15 chars, ok\n- looksLikeIngredient: no\n- startsWithNumber: no\n- looksLikeMetadata: no\n- isLikelyGarbled: checking the vowel ratio (4 vowels out of 10 letters = 0.4, which passes), and running through the garbled detection patterns—no periods, and the multi-word check is evaluating whether individual tokens like \"/\" and \"Jesien\" match the garbled criteria.\n\nThe \"/\" token fails the lowercase check, \"Jesien\" starts uppercase, \"Zupy\" starts uppercase, so no garbled word is detected. The function returns false (not garbled), so the line passes all hard filters and becomes a candidate.\n\nNow with Fix A, checking `(text.match(/\\//g) || []).length >= 2` on \"/ Jesien / Zupy\" finds 2 slashes, so it returns false and blocks this line.\n\nBut I need to verify this doesn't break the SAFFRON test case. Now I'm implementing all four fixes systematically. For the first fix, I'm adding a check that catches single words with lowercase-to-uppercase transitions, which are telltale OCR artifacts. Then I'm tracking which lines are metadata continuations so I can skip them during the merge phase. For the third fix, I'm adding a pattern that recognizes \"DLA\" followed by any token and a serving unit word, which handles a specific OCR resilience case.\n\nNow I need to verify the LABANEH test still works correctly—those four separate lines should merge into a single phrase through the capsCoalesced pass, and I want to make sure \"BALLS\" doesn't remain as a separate entry afterward. The capsCoalesced step happens before the metadata continuation logic, so the test should still pass. Now I need to verify that the metadata continuation suppression won't break any existing tests—looking through them, none have a metadata line immediately followed by a short ALL_CAPS word in the merged output. Let me trace through Fix C carefully to make sure the index tracking works correctly for the LABANEH case, where line 13 contains the metadata and line 14 has the orphaned word. So `MAKES 25 LABANEH` won't trigger a merge run since it's flagged as metadata, leaving `BALLS` to stand alone in the merged lines. When I process the metadata continuation positions, I'm checking if `BALLS` qualifies as a continuation—it's all caps with just one word, so it meets those criteria.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement these changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6950,"cache_read_input_tokens":37252,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6950},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6e03cb61-049b-40c5-8a90-8c6b34cd394a","uuid":"6f4e9f95-ec41-4046-a3b0-09fa6cdfcf5b"}
